This subtraction yields the exact integral of the funding rate over the duration of the user's position, scaled by their size, without ever looping through blocks or history. This is the "magic" that makes the velocity mechanism scalable to millions of users.9
4.4 The "Claimable" Asymmetry
It is critical to note a distinct variable: claimableFundingAmount. In GMX V2, the amount paid by the dominant side is not necessarily equal to the amount received by the minority side 1:1. The protocol often applies a "funding fee factor" (a tax) or adjusts the claimable amount based on the ratio of OI.
If Long OI is $100M and Short OI is $10M, and Longs pay 0.1%:
Total Paid = $100,000.
If distributed evenly to Shorts ($10M), the yield would be 1%.
The protocol tracks longTokenClaimableFundingAmountPerSize separately to ensure accurate distribution and to potentially siphon protocol revenue.9
5. Parameterization Analysis: The Economics of Stiffness
The behavior of the integral controller—whether it is "loose" (slow to react) or "stiff" (aggressive)—is strictly defined by the parameters set in the DataStore. Analyzing the live parameters on Arbitrum (ETH-USD) reveals the protocol's specific risk tolerance profile.
5.1 Analysis of Live Parameters (ETH-USD Arbitrum)
Based on recent governance updates and chain data, the typical configuration for blue-chip assets is as follows 6:
